{{about||the Pakistani field hockey player|Rahat Khan (field hockey)|the Pakistani singer|Rahat Fateh Ali Khan}} {{BLP sources|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox person | name = Rahat Khan | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|12|18|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[British India]] (now [[Kishoreganj District]], [[Bangladesh]]) | alma_mater = [[University of Dhaka]] | occupation = Journalist, litterateur | years_active = 1964–present | known_for = Editor of ''[[The Daily Ittefaq]]'' | notable_works = | awards = [[#Awards|full list]] }}
'''Rahat Khan''' ({{lang-bn|রাহাত খান}}) (born 19 December 1940) is a [[Bangladesh]]i journalist and litterateur. He has written more than 32 novels.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
==Early life== Khan was born on 19 December 1940 in what is now [[Kishoreganj District]].<ref name="jj18Dec2016">{{cite news |script-title=নগর চেতনার কথাশিল্পী রাহাত খান |trans-title=Spirit of the city writer Rahat Khan |url=http://www.jaijaidinbd.com/?view=details&archiev=yes&arch_date=18-12-2016&feature=yes&type=single&pub_no=1754&cat_id=3&menu_id=75&news_type_id=1&index=18 |newspaper=[[Jaijaidin]] |date=18 December 2016}}</ref> He wrote his first story as a student in [[Third grade|class three]]. In his words, "One day a kite pounced on a small tortoise before our eyes. The event shocked me very much and made me tearful. I don't know why but I wrote a story on it and thus my authorial life began."<ref>Interview with Suhita Sultana for ''The Daily Banglabazar Patrika'' (27 February 1997)</ref> Khan completed a degree in economics and philosophy at [[Ananda Mohan College]]. He earned his MA from the Department of Bangla Language and Literature at the [[University of Dhaka]] in 1961. For the next eight years he taught Bangla at various colleges, including [[Jagannath College]] in Dhaka.<ref name="jj18Dec2016" />
==Career== In 1969, Khan joined the Bangla-language daily newspaper ''[[The Daily Ittefaq]]'' as assistant editor.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} He would spend over four decades at the paper, eventually becoming its editor.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manik Mia`s journalism was about movement |url=http://thedailynewnation.com/news/55079/manik-mias-journalism-was-about-movement.html |newspaper=The New Nation |date=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Chaos at Ittefaq again over control |url=http://print.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/old/2009/09/27/80009.html |newspaper=The Financial Express |location=Dhaka |date=27 September 2009}}</ref>
In 1972, he published his first collection of short stories, ''Onischito Lokaloy'' (''Uncertain Human Habitation'').{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} The following year he received the [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] for his short stories.<ref name="banglaacademy">{{cite web |url=http://banglaacademy.org.bd/?page_id=1315 |script-title=পুরস্কারপ্রাপ্ত লেখক-তালিকা |trans-title=Awarded Authors |language=bn |website=Bangla Academy |access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref> He produced further volumes: ''Ontohin Jatra'' (''The Eternal Journey''), ''Bhalo Monder Taka'' (''Money for Good and Evil''), and in 1983, ''Apel Songbad'' (''News of the Apple''). In the early 1980s he published his debut novel, ''Omol Dhobol Chakri'' (''Milk-White Service''). He continued writing novels into the 1990s.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
After leaving ''Ittefaq'', he was advisory editor of ''Dainik Bartoman'' and served on the board of directors of the national news agency, [[Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha]] (BSS). In March 2016, he was appointed to a two-and-a-half year term as chairman of the board of BSS.<ref>{{cite news |title=BSS Board reconstituted |url=http://www.theindependentbd.com/printversion/details/38424 |newspaper=The Independent |location=Dhaka |date=25 March 2016}}</ref>
== Themes == The middle and upper class life observed in his novels comes out of urban [[Dhaka]] society, while novels such as ''Omol Dhobol Chakri'' explore village life.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
He also considered [[Bengali Language Movement|Ekushe February]] and the [[Bangladeshi Liberation War]] in works such as ''Hey Matoh Bong'' and ''Hey Mohasunyota''.
==Novels== * ''Omol Dhobol Chakuri'' (''Milk-White Service'', 1982) * ''Ek Priyodorshini'' (''A Beautiful Woman'', 1983) * ''Chayadompoti'' (''A Shadow Couple'', 1984) * ''Sangharsha'' (''Clash'', 1984) * ''Shahar'' (''The City'', 1984) * ''Hey Onanter Pakhi'' (''O, Bird of Infinity'', 1989) * ''Modhyomather Khelowar'' (''The Forward Footballer'', 1991) * ''Akhanksha'' (''Desire'') * ''Kayekjan'' (''A Few Persons'') * ''Ognidaho'' (''Conflagration'')
==Awards== * [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (1973) in the short story category<ref name="banglaacademy" /> * Sufi Motahar Hossain Award (1979) * Mahbubullah Zebunnesa Trust Award (1979) * Abul Mansur Memorial Award (1980) * Humayun Qadir Memorial Award (1982) * Shuhrid Literary Award (1975) * Trayi Literary Award (1988) * Cetana Literary Award (1989) * [[Ekushey Padak]] (1996){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
